## The Total Weight Trap

This is the most important thing in this entire guide.

When you see "1 ct tw" on earrings, that means one carat total weight — for both earrings combined. Each ear gets 0.50ct.

Not 1ct per ear. Half a carat per ear.

This surprises almost every buyer the first time. They see "1 carat earrings" and picture a 1ct stone on each side. What they actually get is two 0.50ct stones. The math still works in their favor — two diamonds for the price listed — but the mental image is different.

Here's how to read the numbers:

| Listed ct tw | Per-ear carat | What you actually wear |
|---|---|---|
| 1/4 ct tw | 0.125ct per ear | Very small, subtle look |
| 1/2 ct tw | 0.25ct per ear | Delicate everyday wear |
| 3/4 ct tw | 0.375ct per ear | Noticeable, still modest |
| 1 ct tw | 0.50ct per ear | Most popular size |
| 1.5 ct tw | 0.75ct per ear | Statement without drama |
| 2 ct tw | 1ct per ear | Full carat look, real presence |
| 3 ct tw | 1.5ct per ear | Bold, everyone notices |
| 4 ct tw | 2ct per ear | Red-carpet scale |

The Total Weight Trap catches buyers who compare earring prices to loose stone prices. A [2ct loose cushion diamond](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28884982?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is 2ct for one stone. A "2 ct tw" pair of cushion earrings is 2ct split between two stones — 1ct each.

Now you know. Keep this table open while you shop.

