## The Pair Problem

Cushion diamonds come in two types. [Cushion modified brilliant](/loose-cushion-cut-diamond) — the crushed-ice style. And cushion brilliant — the larger, chunkier facet style.

In a single stone, it doesn't matter which one you have. You made your choice and you wear it.

In a PAIR of earrings, it matters a lot.

If one ear has a crushed-ice cushion and the other has a chunky-facet cushion, they sparkle differently. They don't match. The asymmetry is subtle but it's there — especially in photos and under direct light.

This is The Pair Problem. When you buy a pair of cushion studs, both stones must be the same sub-type.

Reputable earring sets handle this for you. The studs sold as matched pairs are already matched. That's the case with all the certified cushion stud sets in this guide. Both stones in the pair are cushion modified brilliant. The faceting matches.

Where The Pair Problem comes up is if you try to build a custom pair from two individual loose stones. If you source each stone separately, you need to confirm both are the same sub-type — both modified brilliant or both brilliant. Don't mix them.

The same logic applies to color. Both stones in a pair should be within one GIA color grade of each other. Two G stones look identical side-by-side. A G and an I do not. The difference shows up on the ear.

When you buy a certified matched pair, this is already handled. The vendor matches the stones. When you go custom, it's your job to check.

