## Cushion Cut vs Round Diamond Earrings

Most people comparing cushion and round earrings ask one question: which sparkles more?

The honest answer is: round sparkles more. Round brilliant is cut specifically to maximize light return. It has more facets arranged in a precise pattern. When you hold a round and a cushion side by side in the same size, the round is brighter.

But "more sparkle" isn't the same as "better."

Cushion diamonds sparkle differently. The flashes are bigger and slower. The fire — the colored light — shows more easily than in a round. Cushion earrings look warmer. More romantic. Less sharp.

Round earrings look crisp and brilliant from any angle. They're the default for a reason. But they can also look similar to every other diamond stud out there.

Cushion studs stand out. The square-with-soft-corners silhouette is immediately distinctive. If someone notices your earrings and says "those are different," they're probably cushion or oval, not round.

**Cushion wins when:**
- You want earrings that look different, not just expensive
- You prefer warmer, softer sparkle over maximum brightness
- You like the vintage aesthetic that the cushion shape carries
- You already have round earrings and want something else

**Round wins when:**
- You want maximum brightness in all lighting
- You want the most universally flattering shape
- You're buying a first pair of diamond studs and want the safest choice

For price comparison at the same ct tw: round and cushion earrings are priced similarly at certified quality. The [cushion lab stud at 1 ct tw is $1,380](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/earrings/cushion-cut-lab-grown-diamond-stud-earrings-in-14k-white-gold-1-ct-tw-f-g-vs2-si1-item-251851?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). You're not paying a premium or getting a discount for the shape — you're getting a different look.

One more thing buyers ask: do cushion earrings look smaller than round at the same carat? Yes, slightly. Cushion cuts are cut deeper than round brilliants. More weight sits in the depth, less spreads out on top. A 0.50ct cushion and a 0.50ct round won't look the same size on the ear — the round will look a little bigger face-up. Not dramatically different, but it's real. If face-up size matters more than shape, factor this in when choosing your ct tw.

One practical note: round earrings don't have The Pair Problem. Every round brilliant cuts the same way. Cushion studs need matched sub-types. That's an extra step if you go custom, but it's handled automatically with pre-set certified pairs.

